### 🟢 Level 2 ➔ Level 3
* **Objective:** Retrieve the password for Level 3 from a file containing spaces in its name located in the home directory.
* **Core Commands:** ```bash
  cat "spaces in this filename" 
  # OR using the escape characters: cat spaces\ in\ this\ filename

By default, the shell interprets spaces as delimiters separating distinct arguments or commands. Attempting to execute cat spaces in this filename causes the utility to look for four individual files. This is bypassed using two methods:

    Literal Grouping: Wrapping the full file string inside double quotes (""), forcing the shell to read it as a single entity.

    Character Escaping: Utilizing backslashes (\ ) before every space to instruct the shell to treat the space as a literal part of the string rather than a command break. (Achieved efficiently via terminal tab-completion).

    Status: Complete ➔ [FLAG_CAPTURED]
